instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "Commands generated by the User Interface FE (Control Panel sub‑component) are transmitted to the Physical Twin Entity’s Actuation FE. Supported command types include enable/disable of ACC, setting a desired speed, and emergency braking. Commands travel over the same ROS 2 intra‑system messages and Wi‑Fi/UDP inter‑entity channel. The Actuation FE forwards the validated command to the vehicle’s motor and steering servos for execution. The system provides feedback by reporting the updated vehicle state back through the Data Translation FE to the UI, confirming command execution."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The system requires clock synchronization between the physical vehicle and its digital twin with an accuracy of 100 ms, which is the limit imposed by the hardware; safety‑critical vehicular standards typically demand tighter (<100 ms) synchronization, but the implementation settles on 100 ms. This synchronization supports the low end‑to‑end latency needed for ACC computation off‑loading and remote management, implicitly targeting sub‑100 ms round‑trip communication."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "Orchestration is built on ROS2 middleware: each functional entity is packaged as a ROS2 package containing one or more nodes, and entities exchange data via ROS2 publish/subscribe and service mechanisms. The Physical Twin Entity handles sensor pre‑processing, actuation, and device communication; the Digital Twin Entity provides data management, control logic, and the off‑loaded ACC computation; the User Entity supplies 3D visualization and a control‑panel UI. Functional entities are mapped to appropriate compute nodes (on‑vehicle ECU versus cloud) to manage resources and coordinate actions across the system."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The DTS uses a hybrid network architecture. Inside each entity, software components are connected through ROS 2 (DDS‑based) middleware, enabling publish/subscribe communication among FE packages. Between entities (Physical Twin ↔ Digital Twin ↔ User Entity) the transport is a Wi‑Fi link using UDP packets. The design requires low end‑to‑end latency to satisfy real‑time ACC monitoring and remote management; clock synchronization across devices is kept within 100 ms accuracy. No explicit bandwidth, redundancy, or security protocol specifications are provided in the documents."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "Computation offloading of the ACC algorithm is performed by deploying the ACC service on a remote platform, termed the Digital Twin, which may be cloud‑based or edge hardware. Each functional element is packaged as an individual ROS 2 package containing one or more ROS 2 nodes, allowing the services to be started on the hosting platform. Storage of collected data is handled by a Data Storage component (without a directly mapped FE). Scalability is implied by the modular ROS 2 deployment, but concrete scalability mechanisms, storage capacities, or availability guarantees are not specified."
